<section id="interop" class="py-16 border-b border-border">
  <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
    <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-white mb-1 font-sans">5. Interoperability</h2>
    <p class="text-fg-dim text-xs mb-8">Use `.agents` as the source of truth. Project into existing agent tools when needed.</p>

    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="spec-card rounded-md p-5">
          <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-fg-muted uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Canonical model</h3>
          <p class="text-fg-muted text-[13px] leading-relaxed">
            DotAgents Protocol remains the canonical format for skills, notes, sub-agents, tasks, commands, models, and MCP.
            Compatibility tooling should <span class="text-fg">compile out</span> to narrower vendor layouts rather than flatten the protocol.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="spec-card rounded-md p-5">
          <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-fg-muted uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">`dot-agents` as a linker target</h3>
          <p class="text-fg-muted text-[13px] leading-relaxed">
            The <span class="text-fg">`dot-agents`</span> CLI is a good downstream target for linking generated instructions into Cursor,
            Claude Code, Codex, and similar tools. Treat it as a <span class="text-fg">projection/runtime adapter</span>, not the protocol itself.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="spec-card rounded-md p-5">
          <h3 class="text-xs font-bold text-fg-muted uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">Recommended export scope</h3>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-[13px] text-fg-muted leading-relaxed">
            <li><span class="text-accent-green">→</span> Export <span class="text-fg">`agents.md`</span> as shared project instructions</li>
            <li><span class="text-accent-green">→</span> Export <span class="text-fg">`mcp.json`</span> into tool-compatible MCP config</li>
            <li><span class="text-accent-green">→</span> Synthesize selected <span class="text-fg">skills</span> and <span class="text-fg">`context: auto`</span> notes into generated rules</li>
            <li><span class="text-accent-amber">→</span> Keep sub-agents, tasks, commands, models, and bundles protocol-native unless a target adds support</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="code-block rounded-md overflow-hidden">
          <div class="px-4 py-2 border-b border-border text-fg-dim text-xs">generated compatibility view</div>
          <pre class="p-4 text-[13px] leading-loose overflow-x-auto"><code><span class="text-white font-bold">~/.agents/compat/dot-agents/</span>
├── <span class="text-accent-blue">config.json</span>
├── rules/
│   ├── global/
│   │   ├── <span class="text-accent-green">agents.md</span>
│   │   └── <span class="text-accent-green">skills-summary.mdc</span>
│   └── project-name/
│       └── <span class="text-accent-green">workspace-overrides.mdc</span>
└── mcp/
    └── global/
        └── <span class="text-accent-blue">mcp.json</span></code></pre>
        </div>

        <div class="spec-card rounded-md p-4 text-xs text-fg-muted leading-relaxed">
          <span class="text-fg">Flow:</span>
          protocol files merge first, then an exporter generates a compatibility view, then a linker such as
          <code class="text-accent-cyan">dot-agents</code> fans that output into tool-native locations like
          <code class="text-accent-cyan">.cursor/rules</code>, <code class="text-accent-cyan">CLAUDE.md</code>, and <code class="text-accent-cyan">AGENTS.md</code>.
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>